SIMPLE: feel
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Feel
<hw>Feel</hw> <pr>(f⟦emac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Felt</conjf> <pr>(f⟦ecr⟧lt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Feeling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>f⟦emac⟧lan</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>gif⟦omac⟧lian</ets> to perceive,
D. <ets>voelen</ets> to feel, OHG. <ets>fuolen</ets>, G.
<ets>f⟦uum⟧hlen</ets>, Icel. <ets>f⟦amac⟧lma</ets> to grope, and prob.
to AS. <ets>folm</ets> palm of the hand, L. <ets>palma</ets>. Cf.
<er>Fumble</er>, <er>Palm</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To perceive by
the touch; to take cognizance of by means of the nerves of sensation
distributed all over the body, especially by those of the skin; to have
sensation excited by contact of (a thing) with the body or
limbs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who <qex>feel</qex>⟦br⟧
Those rods of scorpions and those whips of steel.</q>
<rj><qau>Creecn.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To touch; to handle; to examine by touching; <as>as,
<ex>feel</ex> this piece of silk</as>; hence, to make trial of; to test;
often with <ex>out</ex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Come near, . . . that I may <qex>feel</qex> thee, my son.</q>
<rj><qau>Gen. xxvii. 21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He hath this to <qex>feel</qex> my affection to your honor.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To perceive by the mind; to have a sense of; to
experience; to be affected by; to be sensible of, or sensitive to;
<as>as, to <ex>feel</ex> pleasure; to <ex>feel</ex> pain.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Teach me to <qex>feel</qex> another's woe.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whoso keepeth the commandment shall <qex>feel</qex> no evil
thing.</q> <rj><qau>Eccl. viii. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He best can paint them who shall <qex>feel</qex> them most.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mankind have <qex>felt</qex> their strength and made it
<qex>felt</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To take internal cognizance of; to be conscious of;
to have an inward persuasion of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For then, and not till then, he <qex>felt</qex> himself.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To perceive; to observe.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To feel the helm</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to
obey it.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 550 --></p>

<p><ent>Feel</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Feel
<hw>Feel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To have
perception by the touch, or by contact of anything with the nerves of
sensation, especially those upon the surface of the body.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To have the sensibilities moved or
affected.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[She] <qex>feels</qex> with the dignity of a Roman matron</q>.
<rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And mine as man, who <qex>feel</qex> for all mankind.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be conscious of an inward impression, state of
mind, persuasion, physical condition, etc.; to perceive one's self to
be; -- followed by an adjective describing the state, etc.; <as>as, to
<ex>feel</ex> assured, grieved, persuaded</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I then did <qex>feel</qex> full sick.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To know with feeling; to be conscious; hence, to
know certainly or without misgiving.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Garlands . . . which I <qex>feel</qex>⟦br⟧
I am not worthy yet to wear.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To appear to the touch; to give a perception; to
produce an impression by the nerves of sensation; -- followed by an
adjective describing the kind of sensation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Blind men say black <qex>feels</qex> rough, and white
<qex>feels</qex> smooth.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>To feel after</b></col>, <cd>to search for; to seek to
find; to seek as a person groping in the dark.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧If haply they
might <xex>feel after</xex> him, and find him.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Acts xvii.
27.</au></rj></p>

<p> -- <col><b>To feel of</b></col>, <cd>to examine by
touching.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Feel</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Feel
<hw>Feel</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Feeling;
perception.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To intercept and have a more kindly <qex>feel</qex> of its genial
warmth.</q> <rj><qau>Hazlitt.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A sensation communicated by touching; impression
made upon one who touches or handles; <as>as, this leather has a greasy
<ex>feel</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The difference between these two tumors will be distinguished by
the <qex>feel</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>S. Sharp.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Feeler</ent>⟦br⟧
